original_note:
Appointments:
Feb 1/23 D0470F C Final Diagnostic Casts Both

Clinic:
Assigned Faculty: [DOCTOR] Progress 3Y3M (Initial bond: 10/8/2019) Appliance: Empower 2 bracket (U7-7; LR7; LR5-LL7); Damon std torque (LR6) Objectives: Resolve crowding, CPHG, RPE Tx plan: FFA, RPE, CPHG Brief tx progress: 10/8/2019: Bonded L5-5 10/29/2019(3W): RPE delivery 11/19/2019(1M): CPHG delivery 5/10/2021(1Y6M): Change 16 x 22 NiTi 6/8/2021(1Y8M): Changed UAW to 17 x 25 SS 1/14/2020(3M): U6's banded. TPA delivered, RPE removed 9/7/2021(1Y11M): Changed LAW to 17 x 25 TMA 10/11/2021(2Y): Changed LAW to 18 x 25 SS 10/31/2022(3Y): Failed appointment 11/14/2022(3Y1M): Changed UAW and LAW to 17 x 25 TMA. Started Right side Class II elastics(Impala) 12/12/2022(3Y2M): Failed appointment 12/19/2022(3Y2M): Failed appointment Appointment Observations: Patient is satisfied with present bite and would like to debond. Showed [GUARDIAN] and the patient the mirror to confirm if they would really like to debond. The patient is not too happy about his overjet. However, since the patient were not compliant with CPHG nor elastics, this is the best bite we can achieve. Patient and [GUARDIAN] was satisfied with the explanation, and would like to proceed with debond. Appointment Procedures: Debonded all brackets. Polishing of all teeth were done. Final records were taken. Patient preferred clear retainers, thus, a prescription for essix retainers were sent NV> Deliver U/L essix retainer NNV> 1M Retainer check, Final CT

Clinic:
No CC. - Seen with [DOCTOR] and [DOCTOR] wire has lost its ligation to the LR1 bracket. Pictures taken with Zandro. Pt is slightly Class II with transverse and vertical issues. UPPER: Prophied and bonded UR2 and UL1-2 with H4 brackets upside-down. Placed 014 CuNITI wire with stops and active open coil at the UL2. Ligate archwire to UL2 with steel tie. Placed lingual buttons lingual to the 5-6's LOWER: Prophied and bonded LR1-2 and LL2 with H4 brackets upside-down. Placed 014 CuNITI wire with stops and active open coil at the LR2. Ligate archwire to LR2 with steel tie. Placed bite turbos on the buccal cusps of the lower 6's. Demonstrated squeeze exercises. Demonstrated elastic wear: linguals of 5-6's to lower 6's and linguals of 5's to lower 3's with Quail (3/16", 2 oz) elastics. Demonstrated oral hygiene. NV: 1. Evaluate transverse and vertical dimensions 2. Evaluate crowding 3. Include UL2 into archwire if possible 4. Intraoral pictures

original_note:
Clinic:
Quad helix removed, adequate U6 derotation achieved. UR6 band became loose, so used BandLock to recement band. Fit #5 Wilson arch into brackets. Bends made to form wilson arch to existing maxillary dentition. Placed springs bilaterally after condensing omega loop. Elastomerics used to engage wire to U2-2. Omega loop opened, thus open coil activated. Pt given 4.5 oz 1/4" elastics to be worn 24/7 besides eating/brushing. NV: check between U5-6 for distalization effort/compliance w/ elastics., reactivate omega loop to condense spring

Clinic:
Retie UAW and add crimp to OCS Faculty Supervising: [DOCTOR] UAW: 020 SS Today I added a lingual button on the UR2 for slingshot. I moved up to 020 SS and I added the crimp and OCS from previous AW. NV: Need to talk to [DOCTOR] to get a plan on how to bring the UR2 into the arch and if turbos are needed to open the bite. The patient is also in buccal crossbite on the left side form the UL4-6 and that needs to be corrected.

original_note:
Clinic:
Patient presents for appliance adjustment. Patient arrived on time: y Minor patient accompanied by: [GUARDIAN] Significant Med/Dental Hx/Changes Med/Dental Hx: nsc Presenting Oh: fair Alerts if any: * Describe if other alert: * Prophy needed? recommend regular recall Radiogrraph needed? * Faculty assigned: [DOCTOR] Covering faculty if different from assigned; * Compliance: good Molar/Canine: II/I OJ/OB: * Treatment progress evaluation: A little more space on mesial of UL2 is needed for buildup. The OCS to push UR2 distally probably pushed the UL1 to close the space between UL1 & 2. UAW: 16x22 Niti, PC UL1 to UR7 LAW: 16x22 Niti Elastics: None Appointment notes: 1. Built up UR2 with composite, polished. New bracket placed on UR2. Stressed to pt and [GUARDIAN] that this is a temporary build up and permanent restoration (crown or veneer) needs to be done with the general dentist. 2. OCS activated between UL1&UL2, and CCS placed between UL2&UL3. 3. PC UL1 to UR7 to close residual spaces on UR and shift midline to R [GUARDIAN] came in today. [GUARDIAN] insisted that the patient looks worse than when he started and had multiple questions/complaints. His main questions were, "Why are there still spaces on the top?" and "Why are you taking even more teeth out (aka wisdom teeth)?" [GUARDIAN] was overall rude and disrespectful. While showing the patient's initial and progress photos, I explained the following: 1. The upper 4's were extracted as pt initially had a large overjet (I said "overbite" for patient's better understanding). After extracting the 4's, most of the extraction spaces were used to retract the upper front teeth back to reduce the overjet. 2. The reason spaces are present around the upper 2's is because we had planned for peg lateral buildups. This was a part of the initial treatment plan, to which [GUARDIAN] and patient both agreed to according to the previous orthodontic residents' notes. Final restorations need to be done at the dentist once braces are debonded. 3. The lower 8's are mesially angulated and are against the distal of the lower 7's. There is an operculum covering the lower 7's and the 8's will not erupt naturally due to the angulation. This impaction may cause the patient pain and discomfort in the long run. While it is up to the patient and the guardian to remove the 8's, this is a recommendation for the patient's oral health rather than for orthodontics. On explaining #2, it was obvious that [GUARDIAN] was unahppy that he had to visit another dentist and pay for permanent restorations (crowns/veneers). Upon explaining #3, [GUARDIAN] accused "And who's fault is that? Because you guys took teeth out and the teeth are now tipping." I explained that this not true as no teeth were extracted on the lower, and that mesiallywisdom teeth are very common. [GUARDIAN] also said that the extractions were done without his approval and since the patient is a minor and the [GUARDIAN] only speaks Spanish, "they don't know." He also complained that he was not allowed to enter the operatory during the extraction at the OS clinic, and said that this is unacceptable as the patient is still a minor. At the end of the conversation, I asked [GUARDIAN] what he would like us to do to make the patient look better, as he kept insisting that the patient looks worse with "spaces everywhere" and that we "did not do things right." He pointed out the shifted midline, for which I explained that the midline shift will be corrected once we finish treatment. [GUARDIAN] said "Well then do what you need to do, if he looks good at the end I'll be happy. But if he doesn't look good, you know what's going to happen." After this conversation, [GUARDIAN] stayed in the operatory while I proceeded with today's appointment. NV: UL2 buildup if sufficient space has been achieved

Patient arrived on time: y Minor patient accompanied by: [GUARDIAN] Significant Med/Dental Hx/Changes Med/Dental Hx: nsc Presenting Oh: fair Alerts if any: * Describe if other alert: * Prophy needed? recommend regular recall Radiogrraph needed? * Faculty assigned: [DOCTOR] Covering faculty if different from assigned; * Compliance: good Molar/Canine: II/I OJ/OB: * Treatment progress evaluation: A little more space on mesial of UL2 is needed for buildup. The OCS to push UR2 distally probably pushed the UL1 to close the space between UL1 & 2. UAW: 16x22 Niti, PC UL1 to UR7 LAW: 16x22 Niti Elastics: None Appointment notes: 1. Built up UR2 with composite, polished. New bracket placed on UR2. Stressed to pt and [GUARDIAN] that this is a temporary build up and permanent restoration (crown or veneer) needs to be done with the general dentist. 2. OCS activated between UL1&UL2, and CCS placed between UL2&UL3. 3. PC UL1 to UR7 to close residual spaces on UR and shift midline to R [GUARDIAN] came in today. [GUARDIAN] insisted that the patient looks worse than when he started and had multiple questions/complaints. His main questions were, "Why are there still spaces on the top?" and "Why are you taking even more teeth out (aka wisdom teeth)?" [GUARDIAN] was overall rude and disrespectful. While showing the patient's initial and progress photos, I explained the following: 1. The upper 4's were extracted as pt initially had a large overjet (I said "overbite" for patient's better understanding). After extracting the 4's, most of the extraction spaces were used to retract the upper front teeth back to reduce the overjet. 2. The reason spaces are present around the upper 2's is because we had planned for peg lateral buildups. This was a part of the initial treatment plan, to which [GUARDIAN] and patient both agreed to according to the previous orthodontic residents' notes. Final restorations need to be done at the dentist once braces are debonded. 3. The lower 8's are mesially angulated and are against the distal of the lower 7's. There is an operculum covering the lower 7's and the 8's will not erupt naturally due to the angulation. This impaction may cause the patient pain and discomfort in the long run. While it is up to the patient and the guardian to remove the 8's, this is a recommendation for the patient's oral health rather than for orthodontics. On explaining #2, it was obvious that [GUARDIAN] was unahppy that he had to visit another dentist and pay for permanent restorations (crowns/veneers). Upon explaining #3, [GUARDIAN] accused "And who's fault is that? Because you guys took teeth out and the teeth are now tipping." I explained that this not true as no teeth were extracted on the lower, and that mesiallywisdom teeth are very common. [GUARDIAN] also said that the extractions were done without his approval and since the patient is a minor and the [GUARDIAN] only speaks Spanish, "they don't know." He also complained that he was not allowed to enter the operatory during the extraction at the OS clinic, and said that this is unacceptable as the patient is still a minor. At the end of the conversation, I asked [GUARDIAN] what he would like us to do to make the patient look better, as he kept insisting that the patient looks worse with "spaces everywhere" and that we "did not do things right." He pointed out the shifted midline, for which I explained that the midline shift will be corrected once we finish treatment. [GUARDIAN] said "Well then do what you need to do, if he looks good at the end I'll be happy. But if he doesn't look good, you know what's going to happen." After this conversation, [GUARDIAN] stayed in the operatory while I proceeded with today's appointment. NV: UL2 buildup if sufficient space has been achievedassistant

Clinic:
Appliance Adjustment 17y F presents to ortho clinic. She passed her driver's test recently, went to Sacramento over ski week to visit family. OH today is poor. Pt did a good job of cleaning her teeth when the wires were taken out, but need to monitor OH and encourage more frequent brushing. OHI given. Did IPR 0.2mm on mesial and distal of L2s. May need to do more IPR as we progress to prevent excessive proclination of lower incisors. Space had opened up, mostly distal to LL2 so that continuous archwire engagement could be achieved at this appt. U: .018 NiTi 6-6 (same wire) L: .016 NiTi 6-6 with ends cinched and figure 8 ties on more rotated teeth Worked with [DOCTOR]: appliance adjustment, bond 7s. Also note, pt is overdue for a cleaning. I discussed with pt's mother, and she said they had been out of insurance coverage, but that they should be starting again soon in April. Due to the patient living far away, the mother suggested scheduling cleaning in June because it will be easier to coordinate wire out/in when pt is not in school.

Jaw deviates slightly to right upon opening and returns to midline upon closure. Recommended treatment is to extract 4 bicuspids to resolve upper and lower crowding to prevent profile change.

Clinic:
Patient presents for appliance adjustment. Patient arrived on time: yes Minor patient accompanied by: * Significant Med/Dental Hx/Changes Med/Dental Hx: no changes Presenting OH: good Alerts if any: * Describe if other alert: * Prophy needed? recommend regular recall Radiogrraph needed? plan for pano at NV Faculty assigned: [DOCTOR] Covering faculty if different from assigned; * Compliance: good Molar/Canine: R: I/I, L: I/III OJ/OB: still 4mm OJ Treatment progress evaluation: slowly UAW: 17x25 TMA LAW: 17x25 TMA Elastics: Continue with same elastic pattern, doubling up on the R side. FTW Bear elastics R: U3-L6, U5-L7 Appointment notes: Patient has been having difficulties wearing her elastics due to her busy schedule being a [GUARDIAN]. We still have slight midline discrepancy. Encouraged patient to try to wear her elastics as best as she can. Pt tested negative to chair side covid test. Today we did upper IPR so that we can retract the upper anteriors and reduce the OJ. IPR performed D of the U1s, M/D U3's, and D of the U4's with slow speed disc. Lightly rounded out the edges of the U1's so they do not look as square. Placed clear PC on the upper arch (had to remove upper steel lace from 6-6 so we can do IPR). All questions answered, pt dismissed in good condition. Notes: - need updated pano - UR1 we will need to do intrusion so that we can have level gingival heights with the UL1 - will need to do lingual root torque in the lower anteriors - we will need to work up to a different wire as TMA doesn't torque very well. Plan for this at next appointment NV: appliance adjustment
